lse, "mention": "estrogens", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9984616041183472, "span": {"begin": 1105, "end": 1114}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:38976"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "alkylphenols", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997380375862122, "span": {"begin": 1116, "end": 1128}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29314"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "organochlorine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992040991783142, "span": {"begin": 1130, "end": 1144}}, {"id": ["mesh:C032279"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "phthalates", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992146492004395, "span": {"begin": 1157, "end": 1167}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9989380240440369, "span": {"begin": 1191, "end": 1199}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogens", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.998196542263031, "span": {"begin": 1279, "end": 1288}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1296, "end": 1298}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1347, "end": 1349}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3320"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HSP 90", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9939767122268677, "span": {"begin": 1399, "end": 1405}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3308"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HSP 70", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9921746850013733, "span": {"begin": 1407, "end": 1413}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2288"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "immunophilins", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9904125332832336, "span": {"begin": 1419, "end": 1432}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3320"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HSP 90", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9972161054611206, "span": {"begin": 1493, "end": 1499}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1543, "end": 1545}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1563, "end": 1565}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:16469"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "17&beta;-estradiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994111061096191, "span": {"begin": 1592, "end": 1610}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:8861", "9079"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "LBD", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.7074832916259766, "span": {"begin": 1662, "end": 1665}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1682, "end": 1684}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3320"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HSP 90", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9957767128944397, "span": {"begin": 1702, "end": 1708}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9985558390617371, "span": {"begin": 1798, "end": 1800}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2100"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER&alpha;-Er&beta;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9890075325965881, "span": {"begin": 1875, "end": 1893}}], "text": "Site of action: The molecular site of action is the estrogen receptor (ER). ERs are&nbsp;members of the steroid hormone receptor family which belongs to a group of nuclear receptors that are transcriptionally activated by ligands leading to downstream activation of many cellular processes. ERs are composed of three principal domains &ndash; N-terminal domain (NTD), DNA binding domain (DBD), and the ligand binding domain (LBD). ER binds to specific DNA sequences known as estrogen response elements (EREs); EREs are generally short sequences located in the promoter region but can also exist in introns or exons (Klinge, 2001). ER-mediated gene transcription is initiated by binding of the DBD to an ERE with two distinct transcriptional activation domains, AF1 and AF2, located on the NTD and LBD respectively (Kumar et al., 2011).  Responses at the macromolecular level: ER&rsquo;s bind to endogenous and exogenous compounds and are activated by endogenous ligands such as estrone (E1), estradiol (E2) and estriol (E3) (Ng et al., 2014). There are numerous compounds (e.g., natural or pharmaceutical estrogens, alkylphenols, organochlorine pesticides, phthalates, etc.) that can act as estrogen agonists or antagonists, and effectively mimic or block the natural effects of estrogens on the ER (Pillon et al., 2005; Schmieder et al., 2014).  ER is part of a multi-protein complex consisting of HSP 90, HSP 70, and immunophilins (Stice &amp; Knowlton, 2008). In this multi-protein complex HSP 90 is the dominant protein and its binding to ER is essential for ER conformational binding of 17&beta;-estradiol (Segnitz &amp; Gehring, 1997). When binding on the LBD receptor occurs ER dissociates from HSP 90 and leads to receptor dimerization which can either be homodimers from the same isoform (ER&alpha;-Er&alpha;) or heterodimers containing one unit from both isoforms (ER&alpha;-Er&beta;) (Fliss et al., 2000). The translocation of these dimers into the nucleus modulates gene transcription (Aranda &amp; Pascual, 2001).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:31:03 +0000 2026"}